The legal battle trailing the naira redesign policy dominated the cover pages of Nigerian newspapers. The Punch reports that the naira redesign policy of the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has pitted three governors of the All Progressives Congress (APC) against 14 political parties, which have threatened to boycott the February 25 election, if the CBN extends the deadline. The newspaper says a federal high court sitting in Lagos has ordered the federal government to suspend the planned concession of the Murtala Muhammed International Airport. The Nation reports that President Muhammadu Buhari said he expected two million votes for Bola Tinubu, APC presidential candidate, from Katsina during the election. The newspaper says labour leaders have explained why the Nigeria Labour Congress (NLC) opted for a consensus arrangement in picking its new president. The Guardian says a high court sitting in the federal capital territory (FCT) has ordered the CBN and commercial banks to go ahead with the full implementation of the naira redesign policy. The newspaper reports that Abdulrasheed Bawa, the chairman of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC), has been committed to prison for allegedly disobeying a court order. Daily Trust says the World Bank said naira and fuel scarcity could hamper the conduct of February and March elections. The newspaper reports that a fire outbreak at the Muna Garage Internally Displaced Personsâ€™ (IDPs) camp in Maiduguri, Borno state, has left many people homeless. Daily Independent says a court has ordered the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) not to take any action at suspending or expelling Nyesom Wike, governor of Rivers, from the party. The newspaper reports Ahmad Lawan, senate president, has commended the ruling of the supreme court affirming him as the APC candidate for Yobe north senatorial district. 